===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

In oracle bone and Western Zhou bronze inscriptions, the left component {{zh-l|*𤔔}} depicts hands drawing out silk threads with a {{zh-l|*壬}}/{{zh-l|*工}}-shaped element at the centre (perhaps a reeling tool or a midpoint marker), representing the act of ordering and sorting silk. The right component is {{zh-l|*𬔖}} (original form of {{zh-l|*刈}}), also carrying the sense "to put in order"; it sometimes appears with {{zh-l|*口}} appended, and some forms further prefix {{zh-l|*言}} at the far left. Compare {{zh-l|*𤔲}}, a related graph using {{zh-l|*司}} on the right, attested in bronze inscriptions for both {{zh-l|*司}} and {{zh-l|*嗣}}.

The right-side {{zh-l|*辛}} of the received form is a graphic corruption of {{zh-l|*𬔖}}, functioning as a phonophoric supplying *l-type phonetic information. The left component {{zh-l|*𤔔}} may itself carry a phonetic hint related to {{och-l|*絲|silk|tr=*sə}}, supplying *s-; together they yield the *sl- cluster of the word.

Within the *slə phonetic neighbourhood, several semantic clusters are discernible: (a) ''continuation, succession, resemblance'' (e.g. {{zh-l|*嗣}}, {{zh-l|*似}}); (b) ''presentation, bestowal, feeding'' (e.g. {{zh-l|*祠}}, {{zh-l|*飼}}); (c) ''display, arrangement, ordering'' (e.g. {{zh-l|*肆}}, {{zh-l|*司}}); (d) ''fibre, cordage, spinning'' (e.g. {{zh-l|*絲}}). The semantic development of {{lang|zh|辭}} itself likely ran: ''to draw out and order silk threads'' → ''to sort out a legal case; plea, testimony'' → ''words, rhetoric'' → ''to take leave; to decline''.

